Engineers use:

int8, int16

float32

compression

sparse arrays

Example:

np.array([1,2,3,4], dtype=np.int8)


Now each number uses 1 byte instead of 8.

So:
👉 You choose trade-offs based on need

A trade-off means:

👉 You gain something, but you must give up something else.
You cannot get both at the same time.

Memory vs Speed

Engineers had a choice:

Option	Advantage	Disadvantage
Fixed-size data	Very fast	Some memory waste
Variable-size data	Saves memory	Very slow

They chose:

Speed over small memory saving

That decision is a trade-off.

Engineers said:

“Memory is cheap. Speed is precious.”

7️⃣ Final perspective (this is the real lesson)

Computer science is never about “perfect efficiency”
It’s about balanced trade-offs:

Choice	Gain	Loss
Fixed-size	speed, simplicity	some memory
Variable-size	memory saving	speed, complexity

Modern systems choose speed + simplicity.

Final one-line takeaway 🔒

👉 Yes, some memory is wasted — but that “waste” buys speed, predictability, and simplicity, which are far more valuable in real systems.
