Why 8 bits? Why 256 values? Why ASCII?

Now your second doubt 👇
Let’s go historically and logically.

5️⃣ Why not 3 bits? Why not 5 bits?

Because:

n bits → 2ⁿ values


Examples:

3 bits → 8 values ❌ too small

5 bits → 32 values ❌ not enough

7 bits → 128 values ⚠️ almost enough

8 bits → 256 values ✅ perfect

6️⃣ ASCII and 8 bits (this is the turning point)

Early computers needed to store:

A–Z

a–z

0–9

punctuation

control characters (newline, tab)

Total needed ≈ 100–120 symbols

7 bits gave:
2⁷ = 128 values


This became ASCII.

But hardware designers thought:

“We already handle 8 bits easily — why waste 1 bit?”

So:

7 bits → ASCII

1 bit → unused / extended

Thus:

1 byte = 8 bits

7️⃣ Hardware evolved around bytes (CRITICAL idea)

Once:

memory chips

buses

registers

CPUs

were designed for 8-bit chunks…

Everything else followed:

16-bit = 2 bytes

32-bit = 4 bytes

64-bit = 8 bytes

Changing this later would:
❌ break hardware
❌ break software
❌ cost billions

So the world standardized on bytes.